 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","title":"robot-redesign/attention: publish actuation outcomes and closed-loop verification events","description":"Publish durable actuation-outcome and reconciliation events so the operator loop becomes closed-loop rather than hopeful. This task exists because once ntm points agents toward existing control commands, the system also needs a first-class way to tell them whether a request started, succeeded, partially applied, timed out, was superseded, or still needs verification.","design":"The work should define how existing robot control commands emit or correlate durable events representing request receipt, request or correlation ID and idempotency semantics where applicable, target reference, expected effect, observed effect, timeout or supersession, and final verification state. It should distinguish direct command execution results from later observed convergence in runtime state, define pending versus confirmed versus failed versus unknown outcomes, and explain how these outcome events appear in digest, attention, diagnostics, and parity transports. This task should improve operator confidence without inventing hidden planner behavior. The system already has explicit actuation commands; the missing piece is trustworthy feedback and reconciliation.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when the attention journal and related surfaces can represent actuation requests plus later outcome or reconciliation evidence strongly enough that consumers know whether to proceed, wait, retry, inspect, or escalate, and can correlate that evidence back to the originating request without guesswork. The result must make write-loop verification a first-class part of the operator story rather than a side effect inferred from unrelated state diffs.","notes":"If an agent still has to grep output or manually diff snapshots to decide whether its own command actually worked, this task is incomplete.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:15:58.089840762Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T03:36:25.360935691Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T03:36:25.360466282Z","close_reason":"Completed: added first-class actuation requested/outcome/verified attention events with request/correlation/idempotency metadata across send, send+ack, interrupt, and REST propagation; verified with targeted tests plus go build ./cmd/ntm, go test -short ./..., and golangci-lint run.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention","events","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:31.247574320Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:17:58.777177886Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:17:59.409702056Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:18:00.040649585Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:28.240300324Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:15:58.089840762Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:18:00.642678033Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:18:01.284467413Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:18:01.916828888Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","title":"robot-redesign/attention: implement deduplication, aggregation, cooldown, and saturation policies","description":"Implement the attention-hygiene layer that turns durable events into an operator-usable queue instead of a stream of repetitive churn. This task exists because even a correct durable journal will feel hostile if repeated source flaps, restarts, unread-mail bursts, or ongoing degraded states spam digest and attention with near-duplicate items.","design":"The work should define and implement how repeated events are deduplicated or rolled up, how cooldown and resurfacing windows work, how persistent conditions escalate from repeated attention items into incidents, how actuation-outcome events and diagnostic evidence are merged into existing items, how operator acknowledgment, snooze, mute, and pin state interact with automatic ranking, and how bounded attention budgets prefer the most decision-relevant items without hiding important recurrence. It should make suppression, aggregation, and operator overrides explainable rather than silent so operators can still tell why an item appeared once, changed severity, stayed hidden, or re-emerged after cooldown or snooze expiry. This is not about hiding bad news. It is about preserving signal-to-noise and operator trust.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when attention and digest can present a concise, prioritized queue that resists duplicate churn, surfaces recurrence intentionally, and makes suppression, aggregation, and operator override rules inspectable.","notes":"If a transient flapping source can drown out real action items or if repeated retries create visually separate clutter instead of a coherent thread, this task is incomplete.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:22:30.983883067Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T03:59:53.847384983Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T03:59:53.846923800Z","close_reason":"Completed: automatic attention cooldown/resurfacing is now inspectable and ranking-aware. Ingress dedup tracks suppressed recurrence, resurfaces the next event with explicit cooldown evidence, and digest prioritization/trace now preserve recurrence under bounded budgets. Verified with focused internal/robot tests, go build ./cmd/ntm, golangci-lint run, and go test -short ./... .","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention","ergonomics","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:47.677398631Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:39.372257751Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:39.923451425Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:22:30.983883067Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:40.492417876Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:41.098650417Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:41.701904070Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","title":"robot-redesign/attention: persist operator attention state and re-emergence rules","description":"Implement the durable operator-attention state that lets users and agents intentionally shape the queue over time. This task exists because the redesign should not force consumers to passively accept automatic ranking forever; they need durable semantics for acknowledged, snoozed, muted, pinned, and manually escalated items so the attention loop becomes collaborative rather than naggy.","design":"The implementation should persist operator attention state in SQLite, keyed strongly enough to survive restarts and correlate with stable item identities or incident fingerprints rather than brittle presentation text. It should define how acknowledged, snoozed, muted, pinned, and manually escalated items influence ranking, visibility, resurfacing, and incident promotion; how manual state interacts with automatic deduplication and cooldown; what happens when an item changes materially while snoozed or acknowledged; and how expired snoozes or changed conditions reintroduce items into digest and attention. It should also expose enough evidence that diagnostics and parity surfaces can explain why an item was hidden, resurfaced, pinned, or force-escalated. This task is where the attention loop becomes collaborative rather than one-way.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when operator attention state is durably persisted and the system can consistently honor acknowledgment, snooze, mute, pin, and manual escalation semantics across restart, replay, resurfacing, and prioritization behavior.","notes":"If users still have no durable way to say not now, keep this visible, or this matters more than the default ranking thinks, this task is incomplete.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:01.332214259Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T04:45:03.277979541Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T04:45:03.277496998Z","close_reason":"Implemented durable operator attention item state with restart/replay/digest/wait semantics plus POST /api/v1/attention/items/{cursor}/state for acknowledge, snooze, dismiss, restore, pin, unpin, mute, unmute, and escalate; build, lint, state/serve targeted tests, and focused reviews are green.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention","ergonomics","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:58.204176406Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.2.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:58.782560632Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:01.332214259Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:59.373249588Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:30:00.001006793Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:30:00.658481031Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.7","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:30:01.238264417Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","title":"robot-redesign/attention: implement watch subscriptions, heartbeats, and adaptive cadence semantics","description":"Implement the long-lived watch semantics that make ntm's event loop safe and pleasant to consume over time: typed event publication, heartbeats, filtered subscriptions, idle-vs-stuck liveness, and adaptive cadence. This task exists because the current redesign is strong on durable replay and operator prioritization, but it still leaves too much ambiguity around what continuous consumers should see when nothing material changes, when sources are slow, or when a consumer only wants a narrow slice of the event stream.","design":"The implementation should define and build how the durable attention journal, transport layer, and source-health logic cooperate to emit typed watch events and explicit keepalive behavior without flooding the system with meaningless churn. It should decide which signals are durably persisted versus emitted only as ephemeral transport keepalives, how heartbeat cadence and liveness deadlines are derived, how filtered subscriptions are evaluated against stable references and event classes, how replay hands off cleanly to live updates, and how source-progress or projection-status annotations tell consumers whether quiet means healthy idle, narrow filtering, temporary source slowness, or a real stuck condition.\n\nThis work should also implement adaptive cadence or similar pressure control so high-churn periods stay responsive while low-churn or degraded periods remain operationally cheap. The goal is not a complex scheduler. The goal is to keep long-lived watch consumers trustworthy, bounded, and intelligible. The implementation should reuse existing cursor, identity, explainability, request-correlation, source-health, and boundedness semantics rather than inventing a parallel model just for streaming.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when ntm can support long-lived filtered watch or streaming consumption with explicit typed events, trustworthy heartbeats, clear idle-vs-stuck semantics, replay-to-live handoff, and adaptive cadence behavior that stays aligned with the shared attention and transport contracts.","notes":"Operator checkpoint: live-only subscriber-aware feed heartbeats landed in internal/robot/attention_feed.go; SSE now suppresses feed heartbeat events and emits richer heartbeat frames with uptime_ms, next_heartbeat_ms, events_since_last_heartbeat, filtered_since_last, dropped_since_last, and subscription_active in internal/serve/server.go. Focused robot/serve tests are green, plus go build ./cmd/ntm, go test -short ./..., golangci-lint run, and touched-file format/import checks. Remaining scoped gaps for bd-j9jo3.4.8: source-health/degraded heartbeat fields, subscriber_count visibility, and last-activity/stale-feed semantics.","status":"in_progress","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:02.724224253Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T05:09:11.844607380Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention","robot-redesign","streaming"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:03.695584425Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:07.706799550Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:02.724224253Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:06.923200325Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:06.156707440Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:05.389480671Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:04.526063040Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","title":"robot-redesign/attention: implement watch subscriptions, heartbeats, and adaptive cadence semantics","description":"Implement the long-lived watch semantics that make ntm's event loop safe and pleasant to consume over time: typed event publication, heartbeats, filtered subscriptions, idle-vs-stuck liveness, and adaptive cadence. This task exists because the current redesign is strong on durable replay and operator prioritization, but it still leaves too much ambiguity around what continuous consumers should see when nothing material changes, when sources are slow, or when a consumer only wants a narrow slice of the event stream.","design":"The implementation should define and build how the durable attention journal, transport layer, and source-health logic cooperate to emit typed watch events and explicit keepalive behavior without flooding the system with meaningless churn. It should decide which signals are durably persisted versus emitted only as ephemeral transport keepalives, how heartbeat cadence and liveness deadlines are derived, how filtered subscriptions are evaluated against stable references and event classes, how replay hands off cleanly to live updates, and how source-progress or projection-status annotations tell consumers whether quiet means healthy idle, narrow filtering, temporary source slowness, or a real stuck condition.\n\nThis work should also implement adaptive cadence or similar pressure control so high-churn periods stay responsive while low-churn or degraded periods remain operationally cheap. The goal is not a complex scheduler. The goal is to keep long-lived watch consumers trustworthy, bounded, and intelligible. The implementation should reuse existing cursor, identity, explainability, request-correlation, source-health, and boundedness semantics rather than inventing a parallel model just for streaming.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when ntm can support long-lived filtered watch or streaming consumption with explicit typed events, trustworthy heartbeats, clear idle-vs-stuck semantics, replay-to-live handoff, and adaptive cadence behavior that stays aligned with the shared attention and transport contracts.","notes":"Operator checkpoint: feed-level adaptive cadence gap closed in internal/robot/attention_feed.go by suppressing ephemeral heartbeats when a recent durable event already proves liveness, while still emitting heartbeat after the quiet period with last_event_time/idle_ms metadata. Independent pane review says no material adaptive gap remains beyond SSE degraded/recovery behavior already handled in internal/serve/server.go. Full local Go verification is still pending because unrelated system-wide Rust compilation is starving the current worktree build/test path.","status":"in_progress","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:02.724224253Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T06:31:57.019518962Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention","robot-redesign","streaming"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.12","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:03.695584425Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:07.706799550Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:47:02.724224253Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:06.923200325Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:06.156707440Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:05.389480671Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.8","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.4.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:48:04.526063040Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.5","title":"robot-redesign/incidents: durable escalation model for recurring operator pain","description":"Introduce a durable incident model for persistent and repeating problems such as crash loops, chronic rate limits, stale reservations, or long-lived stalls. This epic exists because transient alerts are not enough for operators to understand recurring pain or prioritize the work that keeps resurfacing.","design":"Incidents are meant to capture fingerprints, recurrence, severity, lifecycle state, and evidence links so that ntm can distinguish between one-off noise and real persistent operational trouble.\\n\\nThis is a controlled theft from vibe_cockpit's stronger escalation mindset, adapted to ntm's tmux-and-project workflow rather than to a fleet-monitoring worldview.","acceptance_criteria":"This epic is complete when repeated operational pain can be promoted, tracked, surfaced in snapshot/digest/attention, and closed explicitly instead of continually reappearing as disconnected warnings.","notes":"Incidents should help prioritize operator attention, not become a giant secondary ticketing system.","status":"open","priority":4,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":240,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:08.984551518Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:10:20.530945576Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["incidents","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:08.984551518Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":317,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5","author":"ubuntu","text":"Future self: keep the incident model narrow and operator-focused. If it starts feeling like generic ITSM, you've gone too far.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:09Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","title":"robot-redesign/incidents: define incident taxonomy and promotion rules","description":"Define which operator-visible problems stay as transient alerts and which ones should promote into durable incidents. This task exists so recurring or high-cost operational problems acquire lifecycle and memory instead of reappearing forever as disconnected warnings.","design":"The taxonomy should classify incident families such as crash loops, chronic quota pressure, repeated reservation conflicts, sustained stalls, unhealthy source outages, and broken coordination patterns. It should specify severity, promotion thresholds, deduplication/fingerprinting factors, resolution semantics, and how incidents relate to reason codes already used by attention and alerting.\\n\\nThe result should make incident behavior boring and predictable rather than heuristic folklore hidden in code.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained incident taxonomy with promotion and resolution rules that downstream persistence and surface tasks can implement directly.\\n\\nThe taxonomy must explain what evidence accumulates an incident, what keeps it open, what resolves it, and how it differs from a momentary alert.","notes":"Incidents are worth adding only because they reduce operator cognitive load over time. If they become another noisy warning channel, this task failed.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:11.826693809Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:40:09.580941768Z","closed_at":"2026-03-22T03:40:09.580386218Z","close_reason":"Completed docs/incident-taxonomy.md - 16 families, promotion rules, lifecycle","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["alerts","incidents","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:39:53.877190027Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:39:54.341697983Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:39:54.818470055Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:11.826693809Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":326,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead captures a major architectural upgrade: ntm should remember persistent operator pain, not just report the latest symptoms.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:12Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","title":"robot-redesign/incidents: implement incident persistence, fingerprinting, and lifecycle","description":"Implement persistent incidents with stable fingerprints, evidence accumulation, severity, status, and lifecycle transitions. This task exists to turn the incident model into a durable operational memory instead of a conceptual label.","design":"The implementation should define how incidents are keyed, how evidence is appended or summarized, how recurrence is tracked, how resolution and reopening behave, and how incidents connect to source_health, attention events, and runtime projections.\\n\\nThis task should also decide how much historical detail is kept directly on the incident versus in linked events, with a bias toward clear operator semantics over maximal logging.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when ntm can create, update, resolve, reopen, and query durable incidents with stable fingerprints and lifecycle semantics grounded in the taxonomy bead.","notes":"A strong implementation here makes later attention and digest outputs feel much smarter without requiring any hand-wavy 'AI insight' layer.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":210,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:13.201293920Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T03:11:55.136314769Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T03:11:55.135806347Z","close_reason":"Completed: added durable incident fingerprint/family/category fields and migration, CreateOrUpdateIncident fingerprint lifecycle semantics, public GetIncidentByFingerprint queryability, reopen/new-after-window behavior with tests, and 7-day resolved-incident retention via RunGC.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["incidents","robot-redesign","sqlite"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.2.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:39:56.265139624Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.3.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:29.301037774Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:13.201293920Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.2","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.5.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:38:31.484489063Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}

@@ -209,8 +209,17 @@ func (m *FileReservationManager) ReleaseForBead(ctx context.Context, agentName s
 		return nil
 	}

-	_, err := m.client.ReleaseReservations(ctx, m.projectKey, agentName, nil, reservationIDs)
-	return err
+	releaseResult, err := m.client.ReleaseReservations(ctx, m.projectKey, agentName, nil, reservationIDs)
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	if releaseResult == nil {
+		return fmt.Errorf("release returned no result")
+	}
+	if releaseResult.Released < len(reservationIDs) {
